The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control (NCDC) has revealed that Lassa fever has killed 40 Nigerians in eleven states between January 1 to 30, 2022. The Agency further noted that as of January 30, 2022, a total of 211 confirmed cases of Lassa fever have been reported, with a case fatality ratio of 19 per cent). The states with the disease burden are: Bauchi, Edo, Ondo, Oyo, Benue, Taraba, Kaduna, Plateau, Kogi, Cross River, Ebonyi, Enugu, Delta and Katsina. It further disclosed that of all confirmed cases, 82 per cent were from Ondo (30 per cent), Edo (27 per cent) and Bauchi (25 per cent) States. Jealous Lover Kills Girlfriend For Flirting With Customer In… FG, NCF Commemorate 2022 World Wetland Day In a statement, the NCDC said: “In week 4 (between January 24 to 30, 2022, the number of new confirmed cases decreased from 74 in week 3, 2022 to 42 cases. These were reported from Ondo, Bauchi, Edo, Enugu and Delta States. “The predominant age-group affected is 21-30 years (Range: 1 to 80 years, Median Age: 30 years). The male to female ratio for confirmed cases is 1:0.8. “The The number of suspected cases has increased compared to that reported for the same period in 2021. No new Healthcare workers were affected in the reporting. “National Lassa fever multi-partner, multi-sectoral Emergency Coordination Centre (EOC) activated to coordinate response activities at all levels.”